    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="1445"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1445">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.52/440.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of the Navy</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 19, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to the Department’s letter of October
                    10, in regard to the situation of Spanish subjects at Mazatlan, Mexico, I have
                    the honor to inform you that the Spanish Embassy has made inquiry concerning the
                    welfare of the Spanish Consular Agent at Mazatlan, who has been reported as
                    being under arrest at that place.</p>
                <p>The Department of State has the honor to suggest that you send a telegram to the
                    Commander of the fleet in Mexican west coast waters to have the naval vessel now
                    at Mazatlan report as to the welfare of the Spanish Consular Agent.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
